title: New Forbidden Memories Any% Route
content:
To be used for sub 3/3:30 attempts, and potentially World Record attempts.
 
- Start with AT LEAST 2 Dragons and 1 Thunder or 1 Dragon and 2 Thunders
- Take more Raigeki decks, reset more Dark Hole decks
- Leave Farm #1 at 5/4 or a strong 4/4. Reset if above 40 minutes and cannot meet the criteria
- Skip saving for Weevil through Bakura if really strong deck
- Go to Farm 2 after beating Mage Soldier in Campaign
- If no Dragon Treasure or Dark Energy drop before 2:30, RESET
- Generally avoid buying Dragons, buy Thunders instead, you want to have at least 7
- If you get a Trap at any point, A-TEC Pegasus until 2:30
- Potentially skip Seto 2nd if trouble with other Mages. If you do it and lose to Seto 2nd once, skip him and do Final 7
- Generally should enter Final 7 at around 2:35-3:05. First/second try = Sub 3-3:30
 
Final decks should generally look like this:
- 10 Dragons, 8 Thunders, 2 Equips, 2/3 Umis
- 9 Dragons, 7 Thunders, 3 Equips, 3 Umis
- 9 Dragons, 7 Thunders, 2 Equips, 2 Umis, 1 Widespread Ruin
- 9 Dragons, 7 Thunders, 1 Equip, 2 Umis, 1 Megamorph
- 10 Dragons, 7 Thunders, 1 Equip, 1 Umi, 1 Widespread Ruin, 1 DCJ, 1 Megamorph
 
Starting with more Dragons is the key factor to your Initial Deck. The main reason why you want to start with at least 2 is because if you have enough other materials in there such as Machines, Plants and Rocks, you will usually end up getting 4-turn Duels in Farming. Sure, it can take a while to reset until you get a really good deck, but getting a really good Initial Deck makes farming much more efficient and allows you to leave at a much faster pace once you have everything you need.
 
Another reason why you want at least a Thunder is because you will be spending your starchips only on Thunders and nothing more (if you're at a critical situation, you would have to buy Umi as well). Buying Dragons is generally a bad idea because there is a chance you might end up getting a 4th Dragon copy of the one you bought (normally Yamatano or Petit) and you waste starchips.
 
Farming Rex or DMK is nothing new -- I generally leave farming after around the 40 minute mark and then go through the World Tournament because I know my deck now has a confident enough win rate against everyone in WT. That being said, when going for a good time, you now have to look at the value of your deck and if it's good enough to move on from Farm 1. This is now where early resetting comes into play.
 
Normally, DMK drops a lot of Thunders while Rex drops Crawling Dragon #2. If you have at least 4 Dragons before you have 4 Thunders, then it's better to go to DMK. Even if you don't win any Dragons or Thunders just yet, it's better to take out all the useless monsters (Fiends/Insects). However, the main reason why you want a good Dragon/Thunder count early on is because you can almost consistently B-POW the people you normally farm in Farm 2 (Pegasus, Isis, Kaiba, Mage Soldier).
 
The best farming spot, however, is Pegasus. Pegasus can drop Acid Trap Hole at a high rate much like with Umi -- which saves 55 Starchips and gives you the option to buy 2 Thunders instead. Not only that, but with Acid Trap Hole you can A-TEC him repeatedly for good drops. (His chance of dropping a good Equip on A-TEC is 164/2048 -- Dragon Treasure being a 36 and Bright Castle/Megamorph being 64, so about 8%). The same applies to Oscillo Hero #2, which is an 80/2048 chance on BCD -- essentially 4%, and as it is a Thunder, it will significantly help with your Dragon count. All of his duels are mostly clean because even if he starts Bickuribox, Flower Wolf & Dark Witch can take it out with Sun. And unlike Isis' 30k Turtle, you can force Pegasus into attacking with Illusionist Faceless Mage, or just clear it out with something like Queen of Autumn Leaves or Metal Dragon. As long as he doesn't lead MBD, you should normally have no problems. If you let Pegasus fuse it will generally be something like a Crimson Sunbird or sparsely Flame Cerebrus, but those are fine as Dark Witch, B. Dragon Jungle King, Kairyu-shin, Sea King Dragon and Pumpking the King of Ghosts all have Neptune and wall them.
 
Isis can drop Widespread Ruin, although the chances of one are twice as less as Pegasus dropping Acid Trap Hole. That being said -- if you haven't won an Equip yet, but won a Trap, then you have a good chance of winning the 2nd Equip and moving on. Again, both farming spots are generally clean as long as Isis doesn't play a B. Skull Dragon or Pegasus does not play Meteor B. Dragon, although Isis leading a B. Skull Dragon is slightly higher than Pegasus leading Meteor B. Dragon. Your win/loss rate during that farm should be around 35-40/3-5 combined.
 
Mage Soldier is a tricky one. Generally I do not recommend doing Mage Soldier at all unless you feel confident and think you CAN win Dark Energy. To not waste anymore time, I would recommend doing no more than 5 B-POWS. If he does drop a Dark Energy, try going up until maybe 10 Mage Soldier wins to see if you can get another Dark Energy (or at least a Dragon/Tripwire Beast), then go to another farming spot.
 
Kaiba is what is generally your last resort if you're desperate for Dragons or a Trap. Kaiba has about a 30% chance to drop Dragons -- the most out of anyone. Not only Dragons, but much like Pegasus, he also drops Acid Trap Hole at a high rate. And not only ATH, there is Dragon Capture Jar, a nice magic to get rid of any pestering Ultimates or MBDs. However, Kaiba is much more inconsistent to farm compared to Pegasus or Isis as he can lead either Blue-Eyes or the Uranus monsters with 3000 DEF. A-TECING Kaiba also is not TOO bad of an idea as it can give removals (notably Crush Card), or Bright Castle and Dark Energy.
 
At this point, once you see the final decks above, that is when you should go and try to beat the game. Yes, the win rate isn't as high (unless you get absurd luck and have both an MBD and Megamorph = 20% winrate, anyone?) - you will generally have a win rate around 1.5% to 7%, but if going for a good time, you aren't really left with a choice. You do NOT want to try to beat the game with only 1 Equip -- generally because the Final 7 consistently plays monsters within the 3000-4500 range, compared to the Mages where even a simple THTD can work. If you have 2/3, then you have a chance. Making a 3300 or even 3800 THTD is a necessity, otherwise you will 90% of the time lose to Heishin 2nd and later.
 
In the end -- again, just use your best judgment. This guide will mostly be successful for those who want a good time in the category and it will end up being a huge reward if you follow it. Hopefully this route makes Forbidden Memories more runnable and less of a challenge for those who want to try it. Good luck!

title: Basic.yml
content:
# This is a reward file
# Define rewards in here (Items, commands, etc)
# File name is the reward name, without file extention
# This reward is named "ExampleBasic"
# That is what you put as a reward for other plugins, like VotingPlugin
# DO NOT HAVE DUPLICATE NAMES!!

# Do not use ExampleBasic or ExampleAdvanced as rewards, they are disabled from loading!

# Wiki Page: 
# https://github.com/BenCodez/AdvancedCore/wiki/Reward-files

# This is basic reward file
# You can have multiple reward files that contain all kinds of rewards
# Below are some basic things you can have, see the advanced example for more

# You can just remove values you don't want (just delete it)
# If you just want money just have a reward file containg only "Money: 100", for example
# You can simply copy and paste from here what you want
# in other reward files, that is the way they are designed

# If true:
# Only allow one item with chance to go through (from items below)
# If no chance specificied it will only give the first item
OnlyOneItemChance: false
 
# Amount of money to give, requires vault
# Use 0 to give none
# Money is not per world
# Use negative to take money
# May need to use a command if it doesn't work
Money: 1500

# Pick random number between min and max money amount
#Money:
#  Min: 100
#  Max: 3000
#  # If true final value will not contain decimals
#  Round: false

#######
# Experience rewards
#######
# Give player experience (not levels)
EXP: 150

# Pick a random number between min and max EXP amount to give
#EXP:
#  Min: 100
#  Max: 1000

#EXPLevels: 3

# Random amount of EXP levels between 3 to 7
# EXPLevels:
  # Min: 3
  # Max: 7

# Commands to run
# Use %player% for player name
# Remove for no commands
Commands:
- tm give %player% 5
#Commands:
  # Commands here will be run by console
#  Console:
#  - 'say %player% was lucky'
# Stagger is enabled by default, delays each command one tick
# Disable to run all commands the same tick
#  Stagger: true
  # Commands here are run by player
#  Player:
#  - 'vote total'

# The messages are sent when rewards above are given to user
# set to '' to give no message (or just remove the option)
Messages:
  Player: '&e&l | &7You''ve received a rewards! thanks for voting!'
  Broadcast: '&aThis is a broadcast'
  
# Can also do this to message player
#Message: '&aMessage to player'

title: wsf_CONVERT-MGS-TO-TXT
content:
<job id="msg_to_txt">
  <script language="VBScript">

    Dim fso, shell, folderPath, outputPath, file, msg, txtFile, baseName
    Set fso   = CreateObject("Scripting.FileSystemObject")
    Set shell = CreateObject("WScript.Shell")

    ' Current working directory (pwd)
    folderPath = shell.CurrentDirectory & "\"

    ' Output folder inside pwd
    outputPath = folderPath & "txt_out\"

    ' Create output folder if missing
    If Not fso.FolderExists(outputPath) Then
        fso.CreateFolder(outputPath)
    End If

    Set outlook = CreateObject("Outlook.Application")

    For Each file In fso.GetFolder(folderPath).Files
        If LCase(fso.GetExtensionName(file.Name)) = "msg" Then

            Set msg = outlook.CreateItemFromTemplate(file.Path)
            baseName = fso.GetBaseName(file.Name)

            Set txtFile = fso.CreateTextFile(outputPath & baseName & ".txt", True)
            txtFile.Write msg.Body
            txtFile.Close

        End If
    Next

  </script>
</job>

title: Meal
content:
Dinner: Spicy Perdue Chicken Veggie Skillet

Well start using the Perdue Shortcuts now and also rotate some veg.

What to use (for you only):
		8 oz Perdue Shortcuts grilled chicken (one 8 oz bag)
		1 green bell pepper, sliced
		12 cups frozen broccoli florets
		1 cup baby carrots, sliced or halved
		12 tbsp Greek yogurt
		23 tsp chili garlic sauce (like last time)
		1 tsp olive oil
		Splash of water or chicken broth (from your cartons)
		Optional carb:
		EITHER 1 small microwave sweet potato
		OR 1 cup cooked Carb Diem pasta
(Pick one, not both.)

Cooking steps
	1.	Prep veg
		Slice bell pepper into strips.
		If carrots are thick, halve them lengthwise.
	2.	Start the pan
		Non-stick skillet on medium-high.
		Add 1 tsp olive oil.
		Toss in bell pepper + carrots. Saut 34 minutes.
	3.	Add broccoli
		Add 12 cups frozen broccoli.
		Add a splash of water or a couple of tablespoons of chicken broth.
		Cover and steam 35 minutes until veggies are bright and mostly tender.
	4.	Add chicken
		Add the 8 oz Perdue Shortcuts.
		Stir and cook 34 minutes until everything is hot.
	5.	Make it creamy + spicy
		Turn heat down to medium-low.
		Stir in 23 tsp chili garlic sauce.
		Add 12 tbsp Greek yogurt and a little splash of water/broth if its too thick.
		Stir just until creamy and hot (dont boil the yogurt hard or it can curdle).
	6.	Optional carb
		If using sweet potato: microwave one per package directions, serve on the side.
		If using Carb Diem pasta: cook 1 cup cooked portion, drain, and either:
		Toss it directly into the skillet, or
		Serve the chicken/veg over the pasta.

Calorie ballpark (with one carb choice)
		Perdue chicken 8 oz: ~220 kcal
		Veg (pepper + broccoli + carrots): ~80100 kcal
		Olive oil 1 tsp: ~40 kcal
		Greek yogurt 2 tbsp: ~2530 kcal
		Chili garlic sauce (3 tsp): ~3040 kcal

Base skillet: ~380430 kcal

Add one carb:
		Sweet potato (medium): ~120 kcal  total ~500550 kcal
		Or Carb Diem (1 cup cooked): typically ~150180 kcal  total ~530610 kcal

Pick whichever you feel like. Either way you land in your preferred 500600 kcal dinner range with a huge bowl of food.

<?php
function isMyCloudNAS()
{
	if (isset($_SERVER['HTTP_HOST']) && strlen($_SERVER['HTTP_HOST']) > 0)
		$_http_host = $_SERVER['HTTP_HOST'];
	else
		return false;
	$mycloudnas_domains = Array(
        'mycloudnas.com',
        'myqnapnas.com',
        'qcloudnas.com',
        'myqnapcloud.com'
	);
	foreach ($mycloudnas_domains as $d)
	{
		if (strncasecmp(stristr($_http_host,$d),$d,strlen($d))==0)
		{
			return true;
		}
	}
	return false;
}
	if(isMyCloudNAS() == true){
		$extPort = exec('/sbin/getcfg System ExtPort -d 0');
		if(intval($extPort)>0)
			$webAccessPort = $extPort;
		else
			$webAccessPort = exec('/sbin/getcfg System "Web Access Port" -d 8080');
	}
	else
		$webAccessPort = exec('/sbin/getcfg System "Web Access Port" -d 8080');
	$webAccessUrl = 'http://'.$_SERVER['SERVER_NAME'].':'.$webAccessPort.'/';
?>

title: GetAllInstances
content:
#!/bin/bash

# List of all AWS regions (as of 2024)
# Since we don't have ec2:DescribeRegions permission, we'll use a hardcoded list
regions=(
    "us-east-1"
    "us-east-2"
    "us-west-1"
    "us-west-2"
    "af-south-1"
    "ap-east-1"
    "ap-south-1"
    "ap-south-2"
    "ap-northeast-1"
    "ap-northeast-2"
    "ap-northeast-3"
    "ap-southeast-1"
    "ap-southeast-2"
    "ap-southeast-3"
    "ap-southeast-4"
    "ca-central-1"
    "ca-west-1"
    "eu-central-1"
    "eu-central-2"
    "eu-west-1"
    "eu-west-2"
    "eu-west-3"
    "eu-south-1"
    "eu-south-2"
    "eu-north-1"
    "il-central-1"
    "me-south-1"
    "me-central-1"
    "sa-east-1"
)

echo "Checking EC2 instances across all regions..."
echo "Current AWS Identity:"
aws sts get-caller-identity
echo ""

# Counter for total instances
total_instances=0

# Loop through each region
for region in "${regions[@]}"; do
    echo "Checking region: $region"
    
    # Try to describe instances in the region
    result=$(aws ec2 describe-instances \
        --region "$region" \
        --query "Reservations[*].Instances[*].[InstanceId, Tags[?Key=='Name'].Value|[0], State.Name, InstanceType, PrivateIpAddress, PublicIpAddress]" \
        --output json 2>&1)
    
    # Check if the command was successful
    if [[ $? -eq 0 ]]; then
        # Count instances in this region
        instance_count=$(echo "$result" | jq 'flatten | length' 2>/dev/null || echo "0")
        
        if [[ $instance_count -gt 0 ]]; then
            echo "Found $instance_count instance(s) in $region:"
            aws ec2 describe-instances \
                --region "$region" \
                --query "Reservations[*].Instances[*].[InstanceId, Tags[?Key=='Name'].Value|[0], State.Name, InstanceType, PrivateIpAddress, PublicIpAddress]" \
                --output table
            total_instances=$((total_instances + instance_count))
        else
            echo "No instances found in $region"
        fi
    else
        # Check if it's a permission error or region doesn't exist/not enabled
        if echo "$result" | grep -q "UnauthorizedOperation"; then
            echo "ERROR: No permission to describe instances in $region"
        elif echo "$result" | grep -q "AuthFailure"; then
            echo "ERROR: Authentication failure for $region"
        elif echo "$result" | grep -q "not subscribed\|not enabled\|not found"; then
            echo "SKIP: Region $region not enabled for this account"
        else
            echo "ERROR in $region: $result"
        fi
    fi
    echo "---"
done

echo ""
echo "Total instances found across all regions: $total_instances"

title: Slower internet
content:
I've HAD to document a weird story that I needed to document regarding the internet speed on my computer.

I've came home from BSG (charity speedrun event), and decided to stream on monday and tuesday, all went well!
During BSG I decided to work on my stamina/body a bit since I had NO stamina at all, tachycardia on 1 day and whatever. So I bought a treadmill, came into the house on tuesday, which is nicely fast. 
 
On wednesday, I decided to stream but saw that the internet speed was really slow. 7/21 D/U. 
For reference, I have a 500/500 (more but we got high margins) line to my house, but because of powerline, I can only reach 50/50ish in my office. I have yet to pull a cable to the office for good speeds, but this is the easy solution.

So I have rebooted every network device in the house, still issue. One of the LEDS on the Powerline adapter is turning red now. It works, but slow speeds. The wifi downstairs is amazing, so it had to be the powerline.

Just randomly now, I wondered "why now?" I then decided to unplug the treadmill (which is downstairs), because that's the biggest change since the stuff happened. And... Instead of getting 7/21, I got 14/50. I think at the time of testing Steam was downloading something vehemothly cutting down on that, and if THAT is the root cause, I guess I'm unplugging the treadmill after every session. Despite having a plug with grounds plugged into a wall socket with grounds, I think they don't work because I do get shocks from the device on that 1 day I got it.

Anyway, weird story. Internet speed dies because of a treadmill.
